3.Conduct data exploration to identify patterns and relationships across the dataset.

df <- data  %>% select(`Type of ownership`, Rating) 
 df1 <-group_by(df, `Type of ownership`) %>%
      summarise(
    count = n(),
    mean = mean(Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd = sd(Rating, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

7. Then plot the following:

Top 10 Companies with rating greater than 3 and under industry “Consulting”

# d <- data %>% select(Industry ,Rating, `Company Name`) 
top_10 <- data %>% select(Industry ,Rating, `Company Name`) %>% filter(Rating > 3 & Industry == "Consulting" )  %>% distinct() %>% slice(1:10)
ggplot(data=top_10 , mapping = aes(y=`Company Name`,x=Rating)) + geom_point()

Top 10 Companies with rating greater than 3 and under industry “Energy”

d <- data %>% select(Industry ,Rating, `Company Name`) 
top_10 <- data %>% select(Industry ,Rating, `Company Name`) %>% filter(Rating > 3 & Industry == "Energy" )  %>% distinct() %>% slice(1:10)
ggplot(data=top_10 , mapping = aes(y=`Company Name`,x=Rating)) + geom_point()

Top 10 Companies with rating greater than 3 and under industry “Accounting”

d <- data %>% select(Industry ,Rating, `Company Name`)
